elements.content: Solvothermal treatment of metal sulfate and oxalic acid in DMF solution generated three isostructural 3D homonchiral (10,3)-a metal oxalates {(Me2NH2)3(SO4)}2[MII 2(ox)3] (M = Fe in 1, Co in 2, Ni in 3) in which D 3-symmetric supramolecular cation {(Me2NH2)6SO4}4+ formed via electrostatic attractions and 24 N−H···O hydrogen bonds functions as template. The overall structure of 1−3 can be described as interpenetration of coordinate [MII 2(ox)3]2− and supramolecular {(Me2NH2)3(SO4)}+ (10,3)-a nets. Thermal analyses reveal that compounds 1−3 show two-stepped decomposition via metal sulfate intermediates. The magnetic behavior of 1 and 2 exhibits antiferromagnetic coupling between M(II) ions, and magnetic ordering is observed in 2.

elements.content: One of the modern challenges in the field of supramolecular materials is the controlled generation of well-defined architectures from both organic and inorganic building blocks. The bis-chelating coordinating ability of the oxalate (ox) ion has made it a useful and versatile choice as a bridging ligand for the design of two-dimensional (2D) and three-dimensional (3D) networks that have applications in molecular magnets, chiral materials, nonlinear optical materials and polyfunctional materials. From a structural point of view, the basic building subunits in oxalate-based 2D and 3D networks are tris-chelated [M(ox)3](6−m)− anions. Each [M(ox)3](6−m)− anion represents a chiral center with D 3 point-group symmetry, showing either Δ- or Λ-helical configuration. In general, the 2D honeycomb structure results when the [M(ox)3](6−m)− anions of different configuration are alternatively linked, whereas the 3D homochiral 10-gon 3-connected (10,3)-a structure arises by assembling [M(ox)3](6−m)− anions of the same configuration. It should be noted that, in contrast to a variety of cations incorporated in 2D honeycomb networks, the cationic templates for 3D metal-oxalate anionic networks are mainly based on D 3-symmetric tris-chelated transition-metal complexes such as [M(bpy)3] m+, [M(bpy)2(ppy)] m+ and [M(phen)3] m+ (bpy = 2,2-bipyridine; ppy = 2-phenylpyridine; phen =1,10-phenantrholine) and non-D 3-symmetric Ph3MeP+ cation. The discovery of new D 3-symmetric templates are very important because it is believed that D 3-symmetric templates can act as complementary partner of preorganized [M(ox)3](6−m)− subunits in 3D homochiral metal oxalates. In the article, we present the structures, thermal behaviors and magnetic properties of three homochiral (10,3)-a metal oxalate networks {(Me2NH2)3(SO4)}2[MII 2(ox)3] (M = Fe in 1, Co in 2, Ni in 3) in which positive dimethylaminium and negative sulfate groups via electrostatic attractions and hydrogen bonds give rise to D 3-symmetric supramolecular cations {(Me2NH2)6SO4}4+ as templates.
elements.clean_text:
Introduction

One of the modern challenges in the field of supramolecular materials is the controlled generation of well-defined architectures from both organic and inorganic building blocks. The bis-chelating coordinating ability of the oxalate (ox) ion has made it a useful and versatile choice as a bridging ligand for the design of two-dimensional (2D) and three-dimensional (3D) networks that have applications in molecular magnets, chiral materials, nonlinear optical materials and polyfunctional materials. From a structural point of view, the basic building subunits in oxalate-based 2D and 3D networks are tris-chelated [M(ox)3](6-m)- anions. Each [M(ox)3](6-m)- anion represents a chiral center with D 3 point-group symmetry, showing either Δ- or Λ-helical configuration. In general, the 2D honeycomb structure results when the [M(ox)3](6-m)- anions of different configuration are alternatively linked, whereas the 3D homochiral 10-gon 3-connected (10,3)-a structure arises by assembling [M(ox)3](6-m)- anions of the same configuration. It should be noted that, in contrast to a variety of cations incorporated in 2D honeycomb networks, the cationic templates for 3D metal-oxalate anionic networks are mainly based on D 3-symmetric tris-chelated transition-metal complexes such as [M(bpy)3] m+, [M(bpy)2(ppy)] m+ and [M(phen)3] m+ (bpy = 2,2-bipyridine; ppy = 2-phenylpyridine; phen =1,10-phenantrholine) and non-D 3-symmetric Ph3MeP+ cation. The discovery of new D 3-symmetric templates are very important because it is believed that D 3-symmetric templates can act as complementary partner of preorganized [M(ox)3](6-m)- subunits in 3D homochiral metal oxalates. In the article, we present the structures, thermal behaviors and magnetic properties of three homochiral (10,3)-a metal oxalate networks {(Me2NH2)3(SO4)}2[MII 2(ox)3] (M = Fe in 1, Co in 2, Ni in 3) in which positive dimethylaminium and negative sulfate groups via electrostatic attractions and hydrogen bonds give rise to D 3-symmetric supramolecular cations {(Me2NH2)6SO4}4+ as templates.

elements.content: All the starting materials were purchased commercially reagent grade and used without further purification. Elemental analyses were performed on a Vario elemental analyzer. The FT-IR spectra were recorded from KBr pellets in range 400−4000 cm−1 on a Nicolet 5DX spectrometer. XRPD data were recorded in a Bruker D8 ADVANCE diffractometer. Thermal analyses were carried out in air using SETARAM LABSYS equipment with a heating rate of 10 °C/min. The magnetic measurements were carried out with Quantum Design SQUID MPMS XL-7 instruments. The diamagnetism of the sample and holder was taken into account.

Materials and Methods

All the starting materials were purchased commercially reagent grade and used without further purification. Elemental analyses were performed on a Vario elemental analyzer. The FT-IR spectra were recorded from KBr pellets in range 400-4000 cm-1 on a Nicolet 5DX spectrometer. XRPD data were recorded in a Bruker D8 ADVANCE diffractometer. Thermal analyses were carried out in air using SETARAM LABSYS equipment with a heating rate of 10 °C/min. The magnetic measurements were carried out with Quantum Design SQUID MPMS XL-7 instruments. The diamagnetism of the sample and holder was taken into account.

X-ray Crystallographic Study

Data were collected at 298 K on a Bruker Apex diffractometer (Mo Kα, λ = 0.71073 Å). Lorentz-polarization and absorption corrections were applied. The structures were solved with direct methods and refined with full-matrix least-squares technique (SHELX-97). Analytical expressions of neutral-atom scattering factors were employed, and anomalous dispersion corrections were incorporated. All non-hydrogen atoms were refined anisotropically. Hydrogen atoms of organic ligands were geometrically placed and refined with isotropic temperature factors. The crystallographic data are listed in Table ; selected bond lengths and bond angles are given in Table ; hydrogen bond lengths and angles for 1 are shown in Table .

Structures of 1 and 2 were determined in cubic chiral space group P41 32 while structure of 3 was solved in enantiomorphic space group P43 32. The asymmetric unit consists of cystallographically independent 1/6 M(II) site, 1/4 oxalate, 1/6 sulfate, and 1/2 dimethylaminium. Octahedral M(II) ion (M = Fe, Co and Ni) is chelated by the oxalate ligands in the Λ configuration in 1−2 and in the Δ configuration in 3 and it occupies the site with symmetry 32. The Fe−O, Co−O, Ni−O bond lengths are 2.1266(18), 2.102(2), and 2.0805(17) Å, respectively. The cis-O−Fe−O angles are 78.26(9), 92.34(11), and 95.06(7)°, and the trans-O−Fe−O angles are 170.46(10)° in 1; the cis-O−Co−O angles are 78.75(12), 91.31(15), and 95.26(9)°, and the trans-O−Co−O angles are 171.51(13)° in 2; The cis-O−Ni−O angles are 79.93(10), 91.15(11), and 94.69(7)°, and the trans-O−Ni−O angles are 172.38(10)° in 3. The tris-chelated [M(ox)3]4− subunit possesses D 3 point group symmetry and may be described as “trigonally distorted octahedron”. All [M(ox)3]4− subunits in a crystal have same configuration and are linked into 3D (10,3)-a topological homochiral [M2(ox)3]2− network (Figure a). This topological description can be viewed as three sets of interconnected helices of identical helicity. One chiral (10,3)-a [M2(ox)3]2− net has 3D channels that are filled by sulfate and dimethylaminium groups. The S of sulfate also occupies the site with symmetry 32, and thus the SO4 2− group is disordered with D 3 point group symmetry. The dimethylaminium cations come from decomposition of DMF molecules in 1−3, and the N atom of dimethylaminium has 2 symmetry. There exist electrostatic attractions and N−H···O hydrogen bonds between dimethylaminium cations and SO4 2− anions. The H atoms of dimethylaminium cations are geometrically placed with N−H distance of 0.90 Å. Very interestingly, each H of dimethylaminium is hydrogen bonded to four oxygen atoms of SO4 2− anion, with H···O distances of 2.05−2.35 Å in 1, 2.05−2.34 Å in 2, and 2.06−2.32 Å in 3 and N···O distances of 2.906(5)−3.109(2) Å in 1, 2.903(7)−3.078(2) Å in 2, and 2.911(5)−3.035(7) Å in 3 and N−H···O angles of 136.9−157.6° in 1, 136.8−157.4° in 2, and 136.8−157.1° in 3. Each SO4 2− anion is connected to six dimethylaminium cations via electrostatic attractions and 24 N−H···O hydrogen bonds to form supramolecular cation {(Me2NH2)6SO4}4+ (Figure a). Double dimethylaminium cations are connected to two SO4 2− anions via 16 N−H···O hydrogen bonds (Figure b). If SO4 2− anions and double dimethylaminium cations are viewed as nodes and linkers, a supramolecular 3D (10,3)-a cationic network formulated {(Me2NH2)3SO4}+ is formed (Figure b). Clearly, {(Me2NH2)6SO4}4+ cation shows D 3 point group symmetry and matches the symmetry of the tris-chelated [M(ox)3]2− ion (Figure c). The overall structure of 1−3 can be described as interpenetration of coordinate [MII 2(ox)3]2− and supramolecular {(Me2NH2)3SO4}+ (10,3)-a nets (Scheme ). The known (10−3)-a [MII 2(ox)3] nets templated by D 3-symmetric tris-chelated transition-metal complexes are not interpenetrating nets. Related (Ph3MeP)2[NaCr(ox)3] has an interpenetrating structure consisting of coordinate [NaCr(ox)3]2− and supramolecular Ph3MeP+ (10,3)-a nets. It should be noted that the interactions in supramolecular {(Me2NH2)3SO4}+ net of 1−3 are electrostatic and N−H···O interactions while the interactions in supramolecular Ph3MeP+ net are weak C−H···π interactions.

To check whether it is a first-order resolution process, in this case, that the two enantiomers are present in a 1:1 ratio, or a second-order spontaneous resolution process leading to an excess of one enantiomer relative to the other, we performed solid circular dichroism (CD) measurements (KBr pellet) on 2. No apparent Cotton effect was observed, indicating that the two enantiomers are roughly present in 1:1 ratio.

elements.content: Magnetic studies for the related 3D networks have carried out by Julve et al., which shows that magnetic behavior of the [MII 2(ox)3]2− (M = Fe, Co, Ni) anionic frameworks is strongly dependent on the size and diamagnetic or paramagnetic character of the cationic templates. For example, [CoIII(bpy)3][CoII 2(ox)3]ClO4 and [FeII(bpy)3][CoII 2(ox)3] show long-range ordering of weak ferromagnetism due to spin canting while isostructural [FeII(bpy)3][CoII 2(ox)3] shows no magnetic ordering and spin canting. The magnetic behavior of 1 and 2 further reveals that magnetic ordering and spin canting strongly rely on different nature of cationic templates in compounds with chiral 3D [MII 2(ox)3]2− network.

elements.content: Solvothermal treatment of metal sulfate and oxalic acid in DMF solution generated three isostructural 3D metal oxalates. In a crystal of 1−3, all [M(ox)3]4− units have same configuration and are assembled into homochiral anionic [M2(ox)3]2− network that defines cavities of D 3 symmetry. Thermal decomposition of DMF resulted in dimehtylaminium groups, which interact with sulfate via electrostatic attractions and hydrogen bonds to generate supramolecular {(Me2NH2)3SO4}+ network. As can be seen, the D 3-symmetric supramolecular cations {(Me2NH2)6SO4}4+ match well with cavities of D 3 symmetry created by chiral anionic [MII 2(ox)3]2− network and can be a new general template of D 3 symmetry for homochiral metal oxalates.

Conclusion

Thermal decomposition of DMF resulted in dimehtylaminium groups, which interact with sulfate via electrostatic attractions and hydrogen bonds to generate supramolecular {(Me2NH2)3SO4}+ network. As can be seen, the D 3-symmetric supramolecular cations {(Me2NH2)6SO4}4+ match well with cavities of D 3 symmetry created by chiral anionic [MII 2(ox)3]2- network and can be a new general template of D 3 symmetry for homochiral metal oxalates.

Thermogravimetric analyses for 1−3 in air atmosphere and under 1 atm. pressure at the heating rate of 10 °C min−1 were performed on polycrystalline samples, which show that 1−3 are stable up to 200 °C (Figure ). The first weight loss in the range of 200−420 °C in 1−3 corresponds to the removal of dimethylaminium and oxalate and the resulting intermediates are metal sulfates. The second course weight loss in the range 600−700 °C for 1 and 700−800 °C for 2 and 3 is associated with removal of sulfate, and resulting stable residues of 17.4% (18.2%) for 1, 17.6% (18.6%) for 2, and 17.1% (17.5%) for 3 indicate Fe3O4, Co3O4 and NiO.

The χm T value at 300 K is 5.88 cm3 K mol−1 for 1, which is as expected for two weak interacting high spin Fe(II) ions. Upon cooling, χm T monotonically decreases to a value of 0.81 cm3 K mol−1 at 2 K due to antiferromagnetic interactions (Figure ). The χm vs T curve shows no maximum, indicating no long-range ordering. The fitting of Curie−Weiss law in the temperature range 30−300 K gives C = 6.76 cm3 K mol−1 and θ = −42.9 K. The magnetization of 1 at 2 K increases slowly with increasing field, and the saturation is not reached at the highest applied field of 70 000 Oe.

The χm T value at 300 K is 6.23 cm3 K mol−1 for 2, which decreases with lowering temperature down to a value of 0.12 cm3 K mol−1 for 2 at 2 K (Figure ). The fitting of Curie−Weiss law in the temperature range 30−300 K gives C = 7.45 cm3 K mol−1and θ = −83.4 K. The C value in 2 correspond to the effective magnetic moment 5.46 μB per Co, which are higher than the expected spin-only value of 3.87 μB for a high spin Co(II) ion, attributed to well documented orbital contribution. Different from 1, the χm vs T curve in 2 shows a maximum around 19.8 K, corresponding to an antiferromagnetic ordering. The magnetization of 2 at 2 K increases linearly with increasing field, and the value is 0.78 Nβ at the highest applied field of 70 000 Oe. Even large anisotropy of high spin Co(II) ion, no spin canting is observed in 2.
